          "body": "The second sub-unit begins with a proverb so obvious that the audience laughs: of course every jug is filled with wine. God commandeers the truism and inverts it. He will fill the inhabitants of the land — kings, priests, prophets, everyone — not with wine but with *shikkaron*, drunkenness. Stupefaction is both the metaphor and the mechanism of judgment. A drunk cannot navigate, cannot hear clearly, cannot respond appropriately to threat. The image is political and theological at once: Judah in 597-587 BC will make fatally irrational decisions — trusting Egypt, rebelling against Babylon, assassinating its own provisional governor (ch. 41). The drunkenness has a telos: God will 'dash them against each other,' fathers and sons together. The image is that of pottery being smashed — fitting, since the wine-jug proverb began the oracle. The triple refusal of mercy in verse 14 (*pity, sorrow, compassion*) signals that this is not a warning to be negotiated; it is a sentence already being executed."
