          "title": "The threefold exposure — diagnosis of irreversible sin (vv. 20-27)",
          "body": "The chapter's final movement is the most theologically concentrated. God addresses Jerusalem in the feminine singular — a personified woman who was given a flock and lost it (v. 20), who trained her enemies and now finds them set over her (v. 21), who asks 'Why?' and receives the answer she already knows (v. 22). Then comes the chapter's most arresting statement: the Ethiopian cannot change his skin, the leopard cannot change its spots. Therefore Judah, 'accustomed to doing evil,' cannot do good (v. 23). This is not pessimism — it is anthropology. The verb *limmud* (accustomed, trained) implies a habit so deep it has become nature. Theologians from Calvin to Edwards have heard in verse 23 the clearest Old Testament statement of moral inability: the will bent by long practice cannot straighten itself. The scattering (v. 24), the measured lot (v. 25), the stripping of skirts over the face (v. 26) all follow from this diagnosis. The chapter closes not with a verdict but with a question: 'How long will you remain unclean?' It is the lament of a God who has done everything to provoke repentance — enacted the parable, preached the oracle, wept in private, stripped the crown — and still the people will not turn. The answer arrives only in Jeremiah 31:33-34, where God promises to do what Judah cannot: write the law on their hearts Himself."
