        "body": "Verses 15-17 interrupt the oracle sequence with an appeal in the prophet's own voice — or more precisely, in the voice of the prophet so identified with God's word that the distinction collapses. The command is 'give glory to the LORD your God' (*kavod*). In the context of Jeremiah, 'giving glory' is the antonym of haughtiness (*gavah*, v. 15) — it is the cognitive and volitional act of acknowledging that God is who He says He is, that His word is true, that His verdict on your sin is correct. John Calvin saw in this command the essential movement of repentance: not the performance of ritual acts but the acknowledgment of God's honor and one's own dishonor.\n\nThe urgency is double-temporal. 'Before He brings darkness... before your feet stumble' — the double *terem* (before) in verse 16 establishes that there is still a moment, still a window, still a 'before' that has not yet become 'after.' The darkness metaphor in Jeremiah consistently means military defeat, national collapse, the withdrawal of God's presence from the land (cf. 4:23-28). The 'dusky mountains' (*nesheph* — twilight-mountains) are the treacherous terrain of night-march, where an army fleeing defeat stumbles and falls. Those who are 'hoping for light' — expecting the political deliverance the false prophets promised — will find their hope become darkness. The irony is temporal and epistemological: the moment of expected relief is the moment of judgment.\n\nVerse 17 breaks open the prophet's interior life. 'My soul will sob in secret' — the Hebrew *nephesh* here is Jeremiah's whole self, his inmost being. He does not weep for effect; he weeps in hiddenness, in the privacy of genuine grief. The flock of the LORD taken captive is both a pastoral image (Ezekiel 34 will develop the sheep-and-shepherd metaphor at length) and a covenantal one: these are Yahweh's own people, the flock He promised to shepherd. Jeremiah's tears here are a participation in the pathos of God — what Heschel called the prophetic consciousness of divine suffering. The prophet who pronounces judgment also weeps over what the judgment finds necessary.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kavod* (glory, v. 16) in the imperative — 'give glory' — is the vocabulary of temple worship pressed into ethical and responsive shape. *Mistar* (in secret, v. 17) — a concealed or hidden place; Jeremiah's weeping is not for the audience. *Eder* (flock, v. 17) — a pastoral word that implies the shepherd's responsibility and the sheep's vulnerability."
